    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:55cd872f-1eff-440e-b9c9-6ad5571be41e",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is an 11-year-old girl from Brno, Czech Republic, who presents to the outpatient paediatric psychiatry clinic accompanied by her mother. She is a slight, pale child with dark circles under her eyes, and she sits tensely in her chair, wringing her hands and frequently glancing toward the door. She speaks softly but articulately, and seems mature for her age in her choice of words, although visibly distressed. She attends the 5th grade at a local primary school, where she is considered a diligent, high-achieving student. Despite her academic performance, she has been struggling intensely for the past seven months with excessive, uncontrollable worrying about school grades, friendships, her parents' health, and global events she reads about online [PMID:3324127].\n\n{patientName} reports persistent difficulty falling asleep, waking repeatedly through the night, and feeling unrested in the mornings [PMID:39295670]. She frequently complains to her mother of stomach aches and headaches before school, and her teacher has noted that she appears distracted and struggles to concentrate during lessons [PMID:3324127]. On several occasions she has experienced episodes of racing heart and sweating during class presentations, which have made her increasingly avoidant of group activities [MEDDIALOG:F41.1:2]. She has started refusing extracurricular activities she previously enjoyed, including a children's folk-dance group and swimming lessons.\n\nAt home, {patientName} is the elder of two children; her younger brother is 8 years old. Her parents are both employed — her father as an IT engineer and her mother as a secondary school teacher. The family lives in a comfortable flat in the city centre. {patientName} enjoys drawing, reading fantasy novels, and playing with her cat. She has a small but close group of friends, though she has been socialising less frequently over recent months due to fatigue and worry. She does not use alcohol or any recreational substances. She eats a balanced diet but has had reduced appetite lately, with weight stable on her growth chart.\n\nHer irritability has increased at home, and she occasionally cries without being able to explain why [PMID:39295670]. Her mother describes her as a \"born worrier\" even from toddlerhood. On examination, {patientName}'s vital signs show a mildly elevated heart rate of 98 bpm [MEDDIALOG:F41.1:2]. She is oriented and cooperative, with no evidence of psychosis or suicidal ideation. The clinical picture — excessive, difficult-to-control worry, physical complaints, insomnia, irritability, and impaired functioning — is consistent with Generalised Anxiety Disorder [PMID:3324127]."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:d7f9235e-697b-4700-98e8-7ced11fc95f0",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} has no prior psychiatric hospitalisations. She was diagnosed with GAD at this outpatient visit, following seven months of escalating worry, insomnia, and somatic complaints [PMID:3324127, PMID:39295670]. There is no history of trauma, major medical illness, or previous psychiatric medication. She had a mild upper respiratory tract infection treated with amoxicillin approximately one year ago — she developed urticaria during that course, and amoxicillin has since been documented as an allergy. No history of seizures, head injury, or thyroid disease. Developmental milestones were all met on time. She has never used alcohol, tobacco, or recreational substances. {patientName} leads a predominantly sedentary lifestyle outside of school, spending significant time on homework and reading; she previously attended folk-dance and swimming but has withdrawn in recent months [PMID:3324127]. Her sleep hygiene is poor: she uses a tablet in bed and has inconsistent bedtimes [PMID:39295670]. Baseline investigations including CBC, TSH, fasting glucose, and ECG have been ordered to exclude organic causes of her symptoms [MEDDIALOG:F41.1:2, MEDDIALOG:F41.1:5]. There is a family history of anxiety disorder in her mother and depressive disorder in her maternal grandmother."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
